  "prompt": "What are the entry requirements for the University of Melbourne?",
  "response": "The entry requirements for the University of Melbourne vary greatly depending on the program and your background (e.g., domestic student, international student, type of prior qualifications).  Here's a general overview, but **it is crucial to check the specific requirements for the program you are interested in on the University of Melbourne website.**\n\n**General Categories:**\n\n*   **Undergraduate Programs (Bachelor's Degrees):**\n\n    *   **Australian Year 12 (ATAR):**  The most common pathway for Australian students. An Australian Tertiary Admission Rank (ATAR) is required. The required ATAR varies significantly by course, often ranging from the 70s to the high 90s.\n    *   **International Baccalaureate (IB):** A minimum Diploma score is required, which also varies by course.\n    *   **International Qualifications:** Qualifications equivalent to the Australian Year 12 are accepted.  The University assesses each qualification individually. Common examples include:\n        *   A-Levels (UK)\n        *   High School Diploma (US)\n        *   Other country-specific qualifications.\n    *   **Foundation Studies:**  If your secondary schooling does not meet the direct entry requirements, you may be eligible for a Foundation Studies program (e.g., Trinity College Foundation Studies).  Successful completion of a recognized Foundation Studies program can provide a pathway to specific undergraduate degrees.\n    *   **Vocational Education and Training (VET):**  Completion of a relevant VET qualification (e.g., Diploma, Advanced Diploma) may be considered for entry into some undergraduate programs.\n    *   **Prior Tertiary Study:**  If you have completed some tertiary study (e.g., at another university), you may be eligible for entry based on your academic results.\n\n*   **Graduate Programs (Master's and Doctoral Degrees):**\n\n    *   **Bachelor's Degree:**  A Bachelor's degree (or equivalent) from a recognized institution is almost always required.  The specific discipline of the Bachelor's degree required can vary. Some programs require a degree in a directly related field, while others may accept degrees from other fields.\n    *   **Grade Point Average (GPA):**  A minimum GPA is usually required. The specific GPA requirement varies by program. Some programs may specify a minimum weighted average mark (WAM) instead of a GPA.\n    *   **English Language Proficiency:**  For international students (and sometimes domestic students who have studied in a language other than English), proof of English language proficiency is required.  Commonly accepted tests include:\n        *   IELTS (Academic)\n        *   TOEFL iBT\n        *   PTE Academic\n        *   Cambridge English: Advanced (CAE) or Proficiency (CPE)\n    *   **Graduate Record Examinations (GRE) / Graduate Management Admission Test (GMAT):**  Some graduate programs (especially in business and some STEM fields) may require or recommend the GRE or GMAT.\n    *   **Relevant Work Experience:** Some graduate programs (especially MBAs and other professional degrees) require relevant work experience.\n    *   **Portfolio/Audition/Interview:** Some programs (e.g., in creative arts, architecture, medicine) may require a portfolio of work, an audition, or an interview as part of the application process.\n    *   **Research Proposal:** For research-based graduate programs (e.g., PhD), a research proposal is usually required.\n\n**Key Considerations and Steps:**\n\n1.  **Identify Your Program:**  The most crucial step is to find the specific program you're interested in on the University of Melbourne website. Each program has its own dedicated page.\n2.  **Check the Program Page:**  On the program page, look for the following sections:\n    *   **Entry Requirements:** This section will outline the specific academic requirements, English language requirements, and any other specific requirements (e.g., work experience, portfolios).\n    *   **How to Apply:**  This section will guide you through the application process.\n3.  **English Language Requirements:**  Pay close attention to the English language requirements. The University of Melbourne has specific score requirements for each accepted test. Make sure your test scores meet those requirements. The requirements may vary slightly for different departments.\n4.  **International Student Information:** If you are an international student, the University of Melbourne has a dedicated section for international students that provides information on visas, accommodation, and other relevant information.\n5.  **Contact the University:**  If you have any questions or are unsure about the requirements, contact the University of Melbourne directly.  You can usually find contact information on the program page or on the University's website. They have a dedicated enquiry service.\n6.  **Application Deadlines:** Be aware of the application deadlines for your program. These deadlines can vary depending on the program and your background (e.g., domestic vs. international).\n\n**In summary, while the information above provides a general overview, you MUST consult the official University of Melbourne website and the specific program pages for the most accurate and up-to-date entry requirements.**\n",
